Q: Binary Search 
Link: https://leetcode.com/problems/binary-search/description/
Question Explanation:
Given a sorted array and need to find the x element from an array and if it doesn't exist return -1. This is standard alogorithm.

Approach:
Brute approach is searching the x linear from starting to ending which takes T.C: O(N) and S.C: O(1).
This question is the standard algorithm which is used for efficient searching in sorted things and takes O(logN) time complexity.

So, here main idea is take low = 0 and high = n-1. and take mid as average of low and high. 
mid = low + (high-low)/2
Now since the array is sorted, check if arr[mid] > x then it implies that x is on left of arr[mid] so we need to move high pointer to mid-1
and same analysis for arr[mid] < x i.e., x will be on right side of ar[mid] so move the low pointer to mid+1

*** if(arr[mid] > x) => high = mid-1 and if(arr[mid] < x) => low = mid+1 ***

Code: 

class Solution {
    public int search(int[] nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.length;
        int high = n-1;
        int low = 0;
        int mid = low + (high-low)/2;
        while(high >= low){
            if(nums[mid]==target) return mid;
            if(nums[mid] > target) high = mid-1;
            else low = mid+1;
            mid = low + (high-low)/2;
        }
    return -1;
    }
}

T.C: O(logN) and S.C: O(1)
